{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3599825,"name":"4391 Programming Mentor","username":"aveeser","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/a/3da27b/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-04-22T13:20:48.898Z","cooked":"<p>So anyone using swerves probably has something where field oriented driving speeds, OR robot oriented driving speeds, are eventually converted to to swerve module states.<br>
How do we go the opposite direction?  As in, if we’re currently driving robot relative via pathplanner or similar, is there a way to determine what the current field oriented speeds are based on the swerve module states being set?</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":3,"updated_at":"2025-04-22T13:20:48.898Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":7,"reads":62,"readers_count":61,"score":47.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":500136,"topic_slug":"getting-field-oriented-speeds-from-swervemodulestates","display_username":"4391 Programming Mentor","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":56643,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/getting-field-oriented-speeds-from-swervemodulestates/500136/1","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true,"can_vote":false},{"id":3599836,"name":"Tim Winters","username":"ArchdukeTim","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/archduketim/{size}/256125_2.png","created_at":"2025-04-22T13:27:41.459Z","cooked":"<p>Just convert to <code>ChassisSpeeds</code> using WPILib: <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/kinematics/SwerveDriveKinematics.html#toChassisSpeeds(edu.wpi.first.math.kinematics.SwerveModuleState...)" class="inline-onebox" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">SwerveDriveKinematics (WPILib API 2025.3.2)</a></p>
<p>this will give you robot-relative speeds, which can then be converted again: <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/kinematics/ChassisSpeeds.html#fromRobotRelativeSpeeds(edu.wpi.first.math.kinematics.ChassisSpeeds,edu.wpi.first.math.geometry.Rotation2d)" class="inline-onebox" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">ChassisSpeeds (WPILib API 2025.3.2)</a></p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":3,"updated_at":"2025-04-22T13:29:43.111Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":55,"readers_count":54,"score":31.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":500136,"topic_slug":"getting-field-oriented-speeds-from-swervemodulestates","display_username":"Tim Winters","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/kinematics/ChassisSpeeds.html#fromRobotRelativeSpeeds(edu.wpi.first.math.kinematics.ChassisSpeeds,edu.wpi.first.math.geometry.Rotation2d)","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"ChassisSpeeds (WPILib API 2025.3.2)","clicks":4},{"url":"https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/kinematics/SwerveDriveKinematics.html#toChassisSpeeds(edu.wpi.first.math.kinematics.SwerveModuleState...)","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"SwerveDriveKinematics (WPILib API 2025.3.2)","clicks":2}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":19820,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"78 AIR Strike Mentor"},"post_url":"/t/getting-field-oriented-speeds-from-swervemodulestates/500136/3","custom_user_title":"78 AIR Strike Mentor","reactions":[{"id":"+1","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3599879,"name":"Martin Nemaric","username":"Martini159","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/278dde/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-04-22T14:22:25.712Z","cooked":"<p>To echo what others have said, so long as you have something along the lines of <code>getPose()</code> that returns your odometry as a <code>Pose2d</code>, and <code>getModuleStates()</code> that returns your module states, something like the following should work…</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">private ChassisSpeeds getRobotRelative () {
    ChassisSpeeds robotRelativeSpeeds = Drive.kDriveKinematics.toChassisSpeeds(getModuleStates());
    Rotation2d robotAngle = getPose().getRotation();
    ChassisSpeeds fieldRelativeSpeeds = ChassisSpeeds.fromRobotRelativeSpeeds(robotRelativeSpeeds, robotAngle);
    return fieldRelativeSpeeds;
}
</code></pre>
<p>Note that our kinematics object is a constant (<code>Drive.kDriveKinematics</code>) but yours might be named or referred to differently.</p>
<p>Hope this helps!</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":3,"updated_at":"2025-04-22T14:22:25.712Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":3,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":40,"readers_count":39,"score":28.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":500136,"topic_slug":"getting-field-oriented-speeds-from-swervemodulestates","display_username":"Martin Nemaric","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":19820,"username":"ArchdukeTim","name":"Tim Winters","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/archduketim/{size}/256125_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":56673,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/getting-field-oriented-speeds-from-swervemodulestates/500136/4","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":true,"topic_accepted_answer":true}],"stream":[3599825,3599836,3599879]},"timeline_lookup":[[1,172]],"suggested_topics":[{"fancy_title":"Trouble with YAGSL 2025 Beta","id":476325,"title":"Trouble with YAGSL 2025 Beta","slug":"trouble-with-yagsl-2025-beta","posts_count":88,"reply_count":70,"highest_post_number":88,"image_url":null,"created_at":"2024-12-09T13:23:03.852Z","last_posted_at":"2024-12-26T17:02:44.359Z","bumped":true,"bumped_at":"2024-12-26T17:02:44.359Z","archetype":"regular","unseen":false,"pinned":false,"unpinned":null,"excerpt":"When we used the 2024 version of YAGSL, everything was worki